01-01-1900
America Divided!
President Buchanan unable to solve the Crisis!
Jefferson Davis to lead the Confederacy!
Texas Votes 3 to 1 to secede!
Gen'l. Twiggs surrenders U.S. Armaments!
The Election of 1860.
21
\tThe Union is dissolved! Just to-day we hear reports of the Texas secession referendum votes being counted, and the State preparing to leave the Union. While it's not yet official, Texas can already be considered the seventh State in the Confederate States of America.\n\tThis comes as no surprise just weeks after Gen'l. Twiggs, in command of the Department of Texas, surrendered his entire U.S. Army property, including 20 bases and 44 guns, to the Confederacy, with President Buchanan infuriated over this "treason".\n\tNews from U.S. Forts Pickens in Pensacola and Sumter in Charleston Harbor are also in, with the garrison commanders refusing to surrender their posts. This could boil over and escalate the extremely tense situation towards open hostilities.\n\tIn Europe the Empires of Great Britain and France are watching the developments carefully, with envoys from both the Northern and Southern states crossing the Atlantic to influence European opinion about the situation in America.

