01-01-1900
The British Beaten!
Panic In Canada!
The Redcoats In Retreat!
The Empire Humiliated!
Despair in the Confederacy!
Royal Navy in Retreat.
16
\tThe British intervention in the American Civil War has ended in a humiliation. Union armies and Naval forces have dealt such a decisive blow to the historical 'Arch Enemy', that any further actions against the Union are renderred impossible.\n\tWith the World's mightiest Navy forced to step back, and the elite redcoats in full retreat, the Province of Canada is in turmoil, with the citizenry panicking and militias deserting en masse. In the Union States, people gather in the streets and markets to celebrate, with flags from the Wars of Independence and 1812 proudly on display.\n\tThough the British have taken a thrashing, it's the Confederacy that is hit the hardest. Losing the world's mightiest military as an ally is a huge shock, and the whole country is in mourning. With the Union flanks now completely secured, its armies can fully focus on dealing a similar blow to the Confederate armies. 

