01-11-1861
Convention held in London!
Mexico under threat of an Invasion!
British, Spanish, French to send troops!
Napoleon III to conquer Mexico?
A military adventure for free trade?
French Emperor Napoleon III.
11
\tNews has arrived from London, where the European superpowers Great Britain, France and Spain have held a meeting, agreeing to what is called the Convention of London, which is an effort to extract the repayment of depts from the President of Mexico, Benito Juarez.\n\tThe Europeans are said to have agreed on a military adventure to pressure Mexico. What the French Emperor Napoleon III calls a foreign policy commitment to free trade, is a prime example of Europe taking advantage of the American Civil War. The United States is in no position to enforce the Monroe Doctrine of 1823, warning against further European imperialism in all of the Americas. While not officially recognizing the Confederacy, the French clearly see her as a buffer nation to protect their Latin reign. The French capitalists are also unofficially supporting the Confederate cause with funds.\n\tWhat this development means for the Civil War remains to be seen.
London, England
