09-05-1862
The French Repulsed!
Battle of Puebla A Mexican Victory!
Battle of Cinco de Mayo!
General Lorencez in Retreat!
Celebrations in San Francisco!
The French Defeated in the Battle of Puebla!
14
\tThe Battle of Puenla was fought on May 5, near Puebla City in Mexico. In the battle Mexican Republican General Ignacio Zaragoza with some 4,500 men repulsed the French under General Charles de Lorencez, resulting in a humiliating defeat for the French. The French lost some 500 men out of an army of 6,500, and are now retreating with Zaragoza in pursuit.\n\tIn the battle, General Zaragoza defended twin forts north of Puebla, with the French mounting three assaults to capture them. In the end, the French artillery ran out of ammunition and the infantry attack went unsupported. After the battle Lorencez waited a few days for the Mexicans to attack, but then started to withdraw to Orizaba with the Mexican Republicans in pursuit.\n\tThe Mexican victory is considered a great strategic triumph for President Juarez, who has declared the date of the battle a national holiday, the Cinco de Mayo. Hispanic communities all the way up in San Francisco are taking part in the celebrations.
Mexico
