16-11-1861
The Trent Affair!
Confederate Diplomats Captured!
Shots fired at a British ship!
British Furious over the Incident!
Great Britain planning an Invasion!
Union Ship stopping the Trent.
15
\tOn November 8, a Union Navy steamer stopped the British ship Trent and captured two Confederate diplomats on their way to Great Britain to negotiate recognition of the Confederacy by the British government. The diplomats, James M. Mason and John Slidell, were brought ashore yesterday and put in prison.\n\tWhile in the North the action is celebrated as just and manly, the British are furious over the incident. It's said that this incident, if not resolved quickly, could lead to a detorieration of relations between the British and the Union. There are reports of British troops preparing to mobilize with the British forces in Canada under General Sir Fenwick Williams being strenghtened and receiving tens of thousands of rifles, as well as an invasion fleet being constructed 24 hours a day, seven days a week in England. It is clear that a confrontation between the British and Union is a real possibility!\n\tThe political leadership in the South is furious as well, but at the same time hopeful that this incident will infuriate the British so far as to cause official recognition of the Confederacy!

