19
29-11-1861
Trent Affair Resolved!
Confederate Diplomats Released!
Lincoln Backs Down!
Relations Returning to Normal?
Invasion Plans Cancelled?
Union Ship stopping the Trent.
15
\tAfter the Trent Affair, where the Union Navy forced a neutral British ship to a halt and to hand over Confederate diplomats Mason and Slidell, relations between the Union and the British Empire have been ice-cold. While the Union politicians were planning their next steps to resolve the affair, reports say the British started full-blown preparations for an invasion!\n\tWhile the release of the imprisoned diplomats has eased tensions, the British preparations have bolstered their strength, both in Canada and at sea. Rumors indicate the British army in Canada is now some 20,000 men strong, well equipped, armed, and with up to tens of thousands of militiamen training in reserve.\n\tLord Lyons, the British minister to the U.S., was summoned by Secretary of State William H. Seward two days ago and as he received the news of the release, the crisis was effectively over. While the Confederacy is disappointed by the events, the diplomats are on their way to London to negotiate British recognition of the Confederacy.
London, England
