22
27-12-1860
Development at Charleston Harbor!
Fort Moultrie Abandoned!
Garrison Moves to Fort Sumter!
Moultrie Rendered Useless by Maj. Anderson!
Picket Ships Surrounding Fort Sumter!
Fort Sumter in Charleston Harbor, SC.
22
\tMajor Robert Anderson, U.S. Army, in command of fortifications in Charleston Harbor in South Carolina, has moved his garrison forces to Fort Sumter. During the night the men of 1st U.S. Artillery regiment abandoned the indefensible Fort Moultrie, spiked the guns and burned the gun carriages.\n\tAnderson's garrison now holds Fort Sumter, which has been surrounded by Rebel picket ships. Attempts to reinforce the garrison with rifles from the U.S. arsenal in the city was prevented by the South Carolina authorities, who call Anderson's actions a breach of faith. Governor Pickens believed President Buchanan promised to keep Ft. Sumter unoccupied.\n\tWith tensions rising in Charleston Harbor, President Buchanan seems to be unable to calm the situation. Fort Sumter controls the inlets to the Harbor and so is a true thorn in Pickens' side. According to the Grand Herald's sources in Charleston, Pickens is preparing to seize the remaining Federal positions and property.
Charleston, SC
