15-01-1861
Fort Barrancas Abandoned!
Lt. Slemmer Occupies Fort Pickens!
Florida Militia Demands Surrender!
Warning Shots Fired!
Fort McRee Abandoned!
Fort Pickens Holds In Florida.
29
\tReports from Pensacola, Florida, have arrived, with tensions there rising after Florida's secession. U.S. Army forces at Fort Barrancas, under the command of Lieutenant Adam J. Slemmer, have withdrawn to Fort Pickens, which they currently hold against the Florida Militia.\n\tDuring the night of January 8, Slemmer's guards repelled a group of local civilians intending to occupy Fort Barrancas. In the struggle the guards fired shots, reportedly the first ones shot in anger during the secession crisis. Two days later, when Florida seceded, Slemmer destroyed over 20,000 pounds of gunpowder at Fort McRee, spiked the guns of Forts Barrancas and McRee and moved to the more defensible Fort Pickens with a force of some 80 troops and sailors.\n\tFlorida Militia Colonel William H. Chase, designer and constructor of the Fort, has demanded Slemmer's surrender, but he has refused. With the fort in U.S. hands, movement in and out of Pensacola Harbor is made impossible, without removing the threat of Fort Pickens first.
Pensacola, FL
