19-01-1861
Secession of Georgia!
208 to 89 Vote to Leave!
Ties with the Union Dissolved!
Constitution of Georgia Being Written!
Georgia Against Abolition of Slavery!
Georgian Convention held at Milledgeville.
26
\tGeorgia became the fifth State to break ties with the Federal Union to-day. The decision to secede was instigated by the stout opposition of President Lincoln's Republican Party and the anti-slavery sentiment the Party stands for. Georgia, a major cotton producer, with a population of over a million, from which 460,000 are slaves, has hereby left the Union to join the four previous like-minded States. The Secession Convention now continues its work by drafting a new constitution. \n\tThe Georgian vote was closer than that in other states, with the first vote giving only a small majority to support secession. But a deep conviction on the part of Georgia, that a separation from North was the only thing that could prevent the abolition of her slavery, eventually won. Reports indicate, though, that many Southerners in Northern Georgia remain loyal to the Union.
Milledgeville, GA
