Jefferson Davis Inaugurated!
President for Six Years!
Confederacy seizing U.S. Property!
State Militias Mobilizing!
Confederate States Army being Formed!
Honorable Mr. Jefferson Davis.
27
\tJefferson Finis Davis, a United States Senator from Mississippi up until January 21, 1861, and a decorated veteran of the Mexican War, has been inaugurated as the first President of the Confederate States of America, with a term of six years. Davis, also a West Point graduate from the class of 1828, served as the 23rd U.S. Secretary of War from 1853 to 1857 under President Pierce, and is well aware that the South lacks the military and naval resources necessary for defense in a war.\n\tDavis has been actively promoting slavery, and has been willing to expand it further, including providing funding to Narciso Lopez and his expeditions to Cuba. Upon hearing about the secession of his home State Mississippi, Davis is said to have called it "the saddest day of his life".\n\tNow, under his leadership, the Confederacy has taken steps to improve security, with militias seizing Federal property, including mints, armories, and forts. The fortifications still held by U.S. Army garrisons in Confederate territory are now in Davis' sights, with every chance of escalation, if the garrisons refuse to yield.
Montgomery, AL
