President of the Confederate States, Jefferson Davis.
27
\tTo-day the Constitution of the Confederate States of American has been Ratified, replacing the Provisional Constitution from February. For the most part the Constitution follows that of the United States, which serves as a basis to it. There are major differences though, for example in the description of slavery and states rights.\n\tAs the policy making within the Confederacy is at full speed, so are defensive preparations. Earlier, in February, a decision was made to establish a Provisional Army of the Confederate States and the Army of the Confederate States of America. In addition each State organizes its own militias commanded by the State Governments, similar to those authorized by the United States' Militia Act of 1792. To supervise the military, a Confederate States War Department has been established.
Montgomery, AL
