\tFort Sumter, standing outside Charleston Harbor, South Carolina, is commanded by Major Robert Anderson of the 1st U.S. Artillery. Anderson's troops have held the fort since South Carolina's secession, falling back from Fort Moultrie in December after having spiked its guns.\n\tSince then a Federal armory in Charleston was captured and on January 9, 1861 a U.S. merchant ship, Star of the West, carrying supplies to Fort Sumter, was fired upon by a battery on Morris Island. South Carolina Governor Francis W. Pickens has demanded the surrender of the fort, but President Buchanan refused.\n\tWhile Major Anderson has been working to complete the defenses of the fort, the Confederate States President, Jefferson Davis, has appointed P.G.T. Beauregard, a former U.S. Army engineer, to command the South Carolina forces in Charleston. Beauregard has been reinforcing the forts and batteries in and around Charleston Harbor with heavy artillery.\n\tAnother U.S. fort under similar conditions is Fort Pickens in Pensacola, Florida, where Captain Vogdes has refused to surrender to the Florida militia.
Charleston, SC
