06-04-1861
Supply Situation at Ft. Sumter Critical!
Lincoln Planning a Relief Expedition!
Sumter's 60 Guns Prepared for Battle!
Heavy Artillery Surrounding Ft. Sumter!
Maj. Anderson Refuses to Surrender!
Fort Sumter Under Siege.
29
\tSince the secession crisis started, two U.S. fortifications have been holding on in the seceded states of South Carolina and Florida. The garrisons have refused to surrender United States property and arms to the state officials. Since the inauguration of President Lincoln, his cabinet has been struggling with the decision of whether to reinforce the forts, and how. Any actions taken might start open hostilities and result in one side being perceived as the aggressor.\n\tRecently the supply situation on Sumter has become critical. President Lincoln has ordered an expedition, commanded by former naval captain Gustavus V. Fox, to land supplies only, and not additional garrison forces. Lincoln has also notified Governor Pickens that an attempt to supply Fort Sumter only with provisions will take place. As this notification was directed to the Governor of South Carolina, not the Confederate government, which Lincoln does not recognize, it is not clear how the Confederate officials will act. The cabinet is meeting in Montgomery, Alabama to discuss the situation.
Charleston, SC.
