Beauregard Issues Ultimatum!
Maj. Anderson Refuses to Surrender!
At 4:30 a.m. Fort Johnston Opens Fire!
Fort Sumter Bombarded!
The Garrison Returning Fire!
Fort Sumter Bombarded!
23
\tOpen hostilities have begun! This morning at 4:30 a.m. Lt. Henry S. Farley, acting upon the command of Capt. George S. James fired the first shot, a 10-inch mortar round, from Fort Johnston towards Fort Sumter!\n\tThe events leading to this escalation started to unfold on April 11, when P.G.T. Beauregard dispatched his aides to issue an ultimatum of surrender to the garrison. The garrison refused to surrender once again, replying that they would evacuate the fort by noon, April 15, unless new orders or supplies were received. Col. Chesnut considered this reply too conditional, and gave the garrison one hour before the besiegers would open fire.\n\tAfter the first shot was fired, 43 guns and mortars from the surrounding forts, batteries, and a floating battery, commenced a general bombardment of the fort. Fort Sumter returned fire at 7 a.m. after breakfast. During the bombardment, the ships and landing boats from Fox's relief expedition were deterred and unable to reach Fort Sumter. With the weather getting worse, it is unlikely that the expedition can help Sumter until dark on April 13.
Charleston, SC
