Fort Sumter Surrendered!
3000 Confederate Rounds Fired!
No Casualties From the Bombardment!
Presd't. Lincoln to Call Militia!
The Civil War has Commenced!
Lowering of the U.S. Flag At Fort Sumter.
24
\tAfter enduring over 3,000 Confederate rounds without losing a man, the Fort Sumter garrison has lowered the U.S. flag and surrendered to Confederate personnel at 2:30 p.m, April 13, 1861. There were no casualties reported from either side during the bombardment, but during a 100-gun salute to the U.S. flag, a pile of cartridges blew up from a spark, mortally wounding two privates and seriously injuring four others. These casualties are officially the first casualties of the American Civil War!\n\tThe garrison has been evacuated from the fort, where a Confederate flag now flies. The Battle of Fort Sumter, the opening battle in the American Civil War, is a Confederate victory. But the North will not stand idle after the attack. President Lincoln has already ordred his cabinet to call in the provisional army. This militia call will surely escalate the crisis even further!\n\tAs both sides are preparing for war, the world holds its breath.
Charleston, SC
