Slavery Prohibited in the Territories!
U.S. Congress to Regulate Slavery!
Popular Sovereignty Rejected!
Joint Effort by Congress and the President!

End of Slavery in the U.S. Territories.
507
\tOn this day, Congress has prohibited slavery in all current and future United States territories. President Lincoln quickly signed the legislation, even though it does not restrict slavery in the states. By this act, Congress and the President have repudiated the 1857 opinion of the Supreme Court of the United States in the Dred Scott Case, which stated that Congress is powerless to regulate slavery in the U.S. territories.\n\tThis joint action by Congress and President Lincoln also rejects the notion of popular sovereignty that has been advanced by Stephen A. Douglas as a solution to the slavery controversy, while completing the effort first legislatively proposed by Thomas Jefferson in 1784, to confine slavery within the borders of existing states.

