Settlers Attacked in Minnesota!
Little Crow on a Warpath!
Redwood Agency Attacked!
Andrew Myrick Killed by the Dakota!
Dakota Attacks in Northern Minnesota,
43
\tYesterday a hunting party of Dakota men killed five white settlers in Acton Township, Minnesota. To-day chief Little Crow has attacked the Lower Sioux, also known as Redwood Agency, killing Andrew Myrick among others. Settlers were given enough time to escape across the Minnesota river, before the Agency was burned down.\n\tTreaties with the Dakota, signed in 1851, ceded large tracts of land in the Minnesota Territory to the U.S. Much of the compensation promised never reached the Dakota people. When Minnesota became a state on May 11, 1858, Little Crow led a negotiation party to Washington D.C. but, again, the Dakota lost more land and the promised payments were not received.\n\tDue to recent famine among the Dakota, representatives of the people have negotiated to obtain food from the Sioux Agencies. It is said that during one such meeting a government representative, Andrew Myrick, told the Dakota to "eat grass or their own dung". According to Little Crow, this was a major reason for commencing war. 

