26-12-1862
The Dakota Surrender!
Little Crow Escapes to Canada!
38 Dakota Prisoners Executed!
Mass Hanging in Mankato!
The Dead Buried in a Trench!
Mass hanging in Mankato.
44
\tAfter the U.S. sent troops to quell the Dakota Uprising, and shortly after the Battle of Wood Lake at Camp Release, most Dakota fighters surrendered. The surrendered fighters were held until military trials that took place in November. Of the 498 trials, 300 were sentenced to death. President Lincoln commuted the sentences of all but 38.\n\tThis day, the Army has executed the prisoners by hanging in Mankato, Minnesota. The mass executions were performed publicly on a single scaffold platform. After regimental surgeons pronounced the prisoners dead, they were buried en masse in a trench in the sand by the riverbank. The remaining convicted Dakota are being held in prison.\n\tThe Dakota War saw 77 U.S. soldiers and up to 800 settlers killed. Some 150 Dakota died during the fighting, in addition to the 38 executed. But the aftermath is still to come, as expelling the Dakota completely from Minnesota is being discussed in Congress.

