15-05-1863
Dakota Expelled from Minnesota!
Survivors Relocated to Crow Creek Reservation!
All Treaties with Dakota Nullified!
A Bounty of 25 Dollars per Scalp!
Defeated Dakota Shipped Away!
Fort Snelling, Minnesota.
45
\tIn the aftermath of the Dakota Uprising last summer, some 1600 Dakota have been held in an internment camp on Pike Island, near Fort Snelling, Minnesota. Many have died in the poor living conditions, as infectious diseases struck the camp.\n\tIn April, the U.S. Congress abolished the reservation, declared all previous treaties with the Dakota null and void, and undertook proceedings to expel the Dakota people entirely from Minnesota. A bounty of 25 dollars per scalp was placed on any Dakota found free within the boundaries of the state. The only exception to this legislation applied to 208 Mdewakanton, who had remained neutral or assisted white settlers in the conflict.\n\tThis May Dakota survivors were forced aboard steamboats and relocated to the Crow Creek Reservation, in southeastern Dakota Territory, a place stricken by drought.

