Organization Patterned After U.S. Army!
Davis Authorized to Call Up to 100,000 Men!
Regular Army of 16,000 Men Planned!
State Militias Commanded by State Governments!
An Act to Establish Regular Army Passed.
522
\tDuring recent weeks the Confederate States Congress has passed acts that effectively have established the Confederate States armed forces. On February 28, 1861, an act establishing the Provisional Army of the Confederate States, or P.A.C.S. was passed, and on March 6, another act established the permanent regular army organization.\n\tThe Confederate Congress has provided for a Confederate army patterned after the United States Army. It is to consist of a large provisional force to exist only in times of war and a small permanent regular army. The Army of the Confederate States of America, A.C.S.A. is the regular army and is authorized to include 15,015 men, including 744 officers. But it seems very unlikely this level will ever be achieved.\n\tConfederate States State Militias on the other hand are already being organized. They are commanded by the state governments, similar to that which the United States' Militia Act of 1792 describes.

