\tThe governments of Cuba and Nicaragua have decided to join the Confederacy to support their fellow Southerners. After Cuba was captured from the Spanish and filibuster William Walker had declared himself President of Nicaragua, the Southern states have had a firm base of supplies overseas. The Confederate authorities in Havana have started the recruitment of volunteers to join militias. Many of these men have combat experience from the Mexican War, and from fighting against the Spanish.\n\tQueen Isabella II of House Bourbon has made it very clear that the loss of Cuba to the bands of American filibusters is not forgotten. While Spanish influence in the Americas has declined after the Spanish American Wars of Independence 1808-1833, the Spanish Empire is still a major naval and military power. After the deterioration of relations between the North and South, and the secession criris, Spanish diplomats have approached Washington D.C. Even if an alliance against the Confederacy sounds far fetched, in a moment of Southern weakness the Spanish could attempt to retaliate, avenging their lost prestige.
