\tOn June 11, Mr. Miller was looking for stray heads of cattle, when he saw smoke in the horizon. Miller rode to Denver and advised Mr. Hungate that it was possible his cabin and family were under attack. Riding to his cabin Mr. Hungate was killed, like his wife and two children, the cabin burned and stock taken.\n\tMr. Van Wormer examined the scene and the bodies were taken to Denver. It was presumed that the attack was by Native Americans, most likely members of Aropaho or Cheyenne tribes. The people of Denver were shocked and want revenge.\n\tThe murder comes after escalations of fighting between the indians and militias in Colorado. In April 1864, the territorial governor called for Colorado Volunteers to "kill Cheyenne wherever of whenever found". After this the number of killings and confrontations has escalated into a full blown Indian War.

