\tFollowing the Hungate massacre in June, the fighting in Colorado has escalated. In August, the U.S. War Department ordered the recruitment of 100-day militias to fight the Natives in the area. On November 29, the troops attacked a camp of Natives, killing and mutilating an estimated 70 to 500 of its population, mainly women and children, while losing 24 soldiers.\n\tThe battle took place after negotiations between Black Kettle of the Cheyenne and the U.S. officials. In these negotiations the peaceful Cheyenne and Arapahos were ordered to relocate, under the threat of their safety. As many refused to to leave, the Colorado troops later attacked them ignoring Black Kettle holding a U.S. flag and a white flag.\n\tIn this massacre the Cheyenne lost eight members of the Council of Fourty-Four, disrupting the Cheyenne power structure, in addition to burying any hopes of a de-esacalation in the fighting.

