A Bill to Preserve the Union!
No Action Against Slavery!
Bill Passes Almost Unanimously!
Thaddeus Stevens Abstained from Voting!
War Aims Resolution Passed by Congress.
51
\tThe 37th United States Congress has passed, almost unanimously, the War Aims Resolution on July 25. This so called Crittenden-Johnson Resolution defines limited conservative goals for the Union effort during the Civil War.\n\tIn the background of this resolution is Lincoln's fear of further slave states seceding. Although the bill makes no mention of slavery, the resolution intends that the Union Government will take no actions against the peculiar institution of slavery; this could retain the loyalty of the Unionists in the slave-holding border states. For this reason, Penssylvania Congressman and abolitionist Thaddeus Stevens has abstained from voting on the measure.\n\tThe house voted in two parts, with the first passing the House with a vote of 121 for and 2 against. The second part passed the House 119-2. On July 25, the Senate rejected the two branch division and passed the entire resolution 30-5. All those who voted against, are rumored to be facing expulsion for taking up arms against the United States.

