Catholics Willing to Serve!
The American River Ganges.
52
\tThe United States, a nation founded by immigrants, has seen the number of new immigrants surge since the 1840s. Known as the land of opportunities, since the industrial revolution in the U.S. the nation has been seen as an attractive target for emigration.\n\tEspecially with the revolutions in the German states in 1848-49 and the Great Famine in Ireland in 1845-1852, hundreds of thousands of new immigrants have moved to America from Europe. This has created unrest, as the poor immigrants are in many cases willing to work in factories for lower pay than Americans. Also, many of the immigrants are of catholic faith, especially those from Ireland.\n\tIn the 1850s a nativist movement called the Know-Nothing Party grew popular in its protest against catholicism in the U.S. Violent confrontations even occurred. All this animosity has eroded Northern unity. But now, with the flames of a Civil War sweeping the nation, many immigrants flock to serve their new country. Maybe their patriotism will win them a place in the home of the brave?
Boston, MA
