A Financial Failure!
Only 35,000 Letters Delivered!
Pony Express Stamp from Last Year.
53
\tThe Pony Express, that started operating on April 3, 1860 between Missouri and California, has now ceased operations and is closing down. The service, during its 18 months of operations, reduced the time for messages to be delivered between the Atlantic and Pacific coasts to about 10 days. Heavily funded by government subsidies, the service eventually ended up being a financial failure, with 200,000 dollars lost and grossing only 90,000 dollars.\n\tThe service relied on fast riders and relay horses along the delivery route. Many such riders gained fame, like William "Buffalo Bill" Cody, or Roberst "Pony Bob" Haslam. The service also saw its own attacks, when in May 1860 Pauite Indians attacked the Pony Express station on Carson River. During this Pauite Indian War, only one mail delivery was lost.\n\tIt was not the lack of courage or dash of the fast riders, but the transcontinental telegraph, that made it obsolete.
St. Joseph, MO
