\tOn February 9, Jefferson Davis was elected Provisional President and Alexander H. Stephens the Provisional Vice President. On March 11, a permanent Constitution was adopted. On May 21, the Congress of the Confederacy passed "An Act to put in operation the Government under the Permanent Constitution of the Confederate States of America". This included the time and date for Presidential elections.\n\tIn this election, Davis and Stephens ran without opposition. The election effectively confirmed the decision that had been made by the Provisional Confederate Congress earlier in the year. 55 electoral votes were needed to win, and Davis secured total of 109, with 97% popular vote. This result can be considered unanimous.\n\tUnlike in the United States, in the Confederacy the President could not be re-elected after serving for six years. The official inauguration will take place on February 22 next year.

