\tPersonal decorations and military medals are considered a European tradition in the U.S. The first proposal for a battlefield decoration for valor was submitted to Brevet Lieutenant General Winfield Scott, the Commanding General of the U.S. Army, by Lieutenant Colonel Edward D. Townsend, but this was turned down.\n\tIn October, the Secretary of the Navy Gideon Welles adopted the idea of decoration to recognize and honor distinguished naval service. On December 9, the Chairman of the Naval Affairs submitted Bill S. 82 as "An Act to further promote the Efficiency of the Navy". This bill included a provision for 200 such medals of honor to be bestowed upon such Navy service members, who distinguish themselves through gallantry in action.\n\tOn this day, President Lincoln signed this bill into law. The Army shall also receive similar such medals in the near future, to "Enlisted Men of the Army and Volunteer Forces who have distinguished, or may distinguish, themselves in Battle during the present Rebellion."

