55
\tOur correspondents in England bring us terrible news from Northumberland, where a severe coal mining accident occured on January 16, resulting in the deaths of 204 men. The beam of the pit's pumping engine broke and fell down the shaft, trapping the men below.\n\tDuring the following days, there were rescue attempts, where the shaft was cleared of debris. Nearing the trapped men, there was a release of noxious gas, and the entire working party had to be rescued. Penetrating further, the miners were found dead. Of the workmen employed at Hartley Colliery, only 55 were left alive, making this one of the worst mining accidents in England. The whole country is in mourning, with Queen Victoria offering her condolences to the families of the deceased.\n\tIn the aftermath of this accident, law makers are already preparing legistlation, requiring all new mines to have two shafts to prevent such disasters in the future.
