56
\tMusic and patriotic songs have been important for the Americans, and during the American Civil War both sides have their own songs to raise spirits. On this day, a most rousing song called the Battle Hymn of the Republic has been published in The Atlantic Monthly. It's a patriotic song authored by writer, and abolitionist, Julia Ward Howe.\n\tThe song derives from an early 1800s folk hymn Glory, Hallelujah. The chorus has been familiar since the 1850s. Now, the chorus and new lyrics are used with the music of John Brown's Body. Howe heard the John Brown version of the song during a public review of troops outside Washington D.C. She was suggested by reverend James Freeman Clarke to write new words for the fighting men's song. She did so staying at the Willard Hotel.\n\tThe Grand Herald predicts this song will become a great hit, and an inspiration to the Union troops, maybe even surviving the war!

