\tTo-day, the U.S. Congress has enacted legistlation barring Union forces from returning anyone to slavery. The officers are no longer to return captured slaves to their owners in the South.\n\tThe Fugitive Slave Act of 1850 is part of the Compromise of 1850. It requires that all escaped slaves, upon capture, be returned to the slaver and that all citizens and officials of the free states must cooperate. As such, it is one of the most hated pieces of legistlation among Northern citizens.\n\tIn the early stages of the war, the Union had no policy on people escaping from slavery, and fugitives were often returned to the slavers. General Benjamin Butler and some other generals confiscated enslaved people as contraband, refusing to surrender them back to slavery. Later, supported by Lincoln, the U.S. Congress enacted the Confiscation Act, which only applied to enslaved people used by rebel enslavers to support the Confederate cause.

