\tTo-day the U.S. President Abraham Lincoln met with a group of prominent African-Americans, all of them free black clergymen, in the White House. This was the first time in history an American President has done so. But the meeting did not auger a decision to give African Americans a voice in government. In essence, Lincoln sought to lobby these men to agree to a divorce. In other words, the President wanted to get black Americans behind his plan to colonize them abroad.\n\tIt can be said, that Lincoln subscribed to the notion, common among whites in the North as well as the South, that it would be impossible for whites and blacks to live together peacefully in a United States without slavery. Lincoln's support for colonization has been long-standing, the seed planted by his political role model, Henry Clay, who also supported the idea.

