\tThis September, when the Prussian House of Representatives were refusing to approve an increase in military spending desired by King Wilhelm I, the monarch appointed Otto von Bismarck Minister President and Foreign Minister. To-day Bismarck appeared before the House's Budget Committee and stressed the need for military preparedness to solve the German Question.\n\tIn this speech, Bismarch said that the "position of Prussia in Germany will not be determined by its liberalism but by its power", and that "not through speeches and majority decisions will the great questions of the day be decided ... but by iron and blood."\n\tThis speech, immediately named the Blut und Eisen -speech, may offer an early indication of things to come in Europe. The Prussian foreign policy is militaristic, and fighting may erupt. Will Grand Tacticians be needed in Prussia during the coming years?
