\tThe London Underground Railroad has officially opened! The world's first underground railway, built in London, has opened its first section between Paddington and Farringdon. The first gas-lit wooden carriages were hauled by steam locomotives, and 38,000 passengers were carried on the opening day.\n\tThe new underground railroad is needed, as the city of London has grown greatly during the early 19th century, with over 200,000 people entering the city, each day on foot in the 1850s. The plans for such a railroad were made promptly, but the project was slightly delayed due to funding difficulties during the Crimean War. Construction began in March 1860, using the "cut-and-cover" method, and during construction thousands of peoples' homes were destroyed.\n\tWith the line now in operation, the underground railroad, very different to the 'one' in America, will be further expanded to help the city of London beat the chronic traffic jams above ground level.
