\tChristmas has been celebreated in numerous ways, even during the Civil War. For example in Massachusetts it is seen as an unnecessary expense and should instead be a day of fasting by the Puritans and Lutherans. In the Confederacy, Christmas celebrations are as joyful as any other celebration in the South. But this year, cartoonist Thomas Nast has, for the first time, depicted Santa Claus in to-day's issue of Harper's Weekly. The good people at Harper's Weekly agreed to lend the illustration.\n\tSanta Claus, evolving most likely from St. Nicholas, a chubby and plump, jolly old elf. In the U.S. Kris Kringle has been a common variant of Santa. Nast's illustration shows Santa, as an American patriot, bringing gifts to Union troops. No wonder the Confederacy sees Santa as a Dutch toy monger, a New England Hottentot.\n\tBut as the Grand Herald is no fake news media, we'd like to point out, that the real Santa Claus, the Christmas Goat, lives in the Russian Grand Duchy of Finland, on top of Korvatunturi, a mountain made out of the skulls of disobedient children.

