\tThe January Uprising began in Russia's Kingdom of Poland this January, when Alexander Wielopolski, the pro-Russian arch-conservative head of the civil administration in the Russian partition, tried to derail the Polish national movement by conscripting the young activists into the Imperial Russian Army for a 20-year service. The rebellion by young Polish conscripts was soon joined by high-ranking Polish-Lithuanian officers and members of the political class.\n\tThis February more radicals in Lithuania, Belarus, Latvia, northern Ukraine and western Russia joined the Uprising. Armouries across the country are looted, and many Russian officials executed on sight. To-day saw the first major military engagement of the uprising between Lithuanian peasants, mostly armed with scythes and a squadron of Russian hussars near Cysta Buda, resulting in a massacre of the unprepared peasants.\n\tThis uprising comes after the Russian Crimean adventure had considerably weakened the Russian Empire of Czar Alexander II.
