\tA number of violent riots have erupted in the major cities of the Union. The riots can be seen as a culmination of working-class discontent with new laws passed by Congress to draft men to fight in the ongoing Civil War. Initial protests against the draft quickly turned into race riots.\n\tThe rioters are mostly white working-class men, many of them Irish immigrants, fearing free black people competing for work and resenting the wealthier men able to afford to pay the 300 dollars commutation fee to hire a substitute to dodge the draft. Already the official death toll has reached one hundred. Mobs have ransacked or destroyed numerous public buildings, Protestant churches, the homes of various abolitionists or sympathizers and many black homes.\n\tWhen the riots started, the police and the military proclaimed Martial law, but as they lacked the manpower to enforce it, the rioting continued unopposed for some time. Now the military is cracking down on the rioters and peace is being restored. 

