\tThe Battle of Shimonoseki Straits was fought on July 16. In the engagement the U.S.S. Wyoming confronted ships and shore batteries of daimyo Mori Takachika, a Japanese feudal lord of the Choshu clan based in Shimonoseki. The battle took place after the Choshu clan started engaging foreign shipping in late June.\n\tThe first U.S. vessel attacked was the merchant steamer Pembroke on June 25. It was unexpectedly intercepted by two European-built warships, with the crews crying "Revere the Emperor and drive out the barbarians!" A French and a Dutch vessel were also engaged during the following days.\n\tIn the most recent engagement, the captain of U.S.S. Wyoming, David McDougal sank two Choshu vessels damaging a third, and dealing damage to the shore batteries before withdrawing. Wyoming was damaged with 4 killed and 7 wounded.\n\tWith the Tokugawa Shogunate unable to handle internal unrest , further showdowns between the Japanese and foreign powers seems likely.
