\tThere is no organized and well-established army nursing system for casualties and no safe or protected institutions to accommodate and treat those who are wounded on the battlefield. This is about to change. On October 26, an International Committee for Relief to the Wounded organized an international conference in Geneva to develop possible measures to improve medical services on the battle field.\n\tThe idea came originally from a Swiss businessman Henri Durant, who witnessed the aftermath of the Battle of Solferino, fought between the French-Italian alliance under Emperor Napoleon III and forces of Austria. In that battle, where the armies combined were well over 200,000 strong, an estimated 40,000 became casualties. Durant was shocked by the suffering of the wounded and the near-total lack of medical attendence. Later he founded the "Committee of the Five" to examine the feasibility of Dunant's ideas and to organize an international conference about their possible implementation. That conference ended on October 29.
