\tReports from Europe confirm, that the Second Schleswig War has begun, with the Prussian Army, along with their Austrian allies, crossing into Danish held Schleswig on February 1. The war is a succession to the First Schleswig War of 1848-52, in which the Danes retained control of the Schleswig and Holstein Duchies.\n\tThe seed for the second war was planted in 1863, when King Christian IX of Denmark signed the so-called "November Constitution", establishing a shared law of succession and a common parliament for both Schleswig and Denmark, which was seen as a violation of the 1852 London Protocol by the German Confederation. After this, in December, 1863, the Confederation marched troops to Holstein and took control of the government.\n\tIn January Otto von Bismarck took the initiative by proposing to invade Schleswig. The other members of the German Confederation refused. Von Bismarck disregarded this, issuing an ultimatum for the Danes to abolish the constitution, which they did not.
