\tOn February 3, the first major battle of the Second Schleswig War was fought at Konigshugel near Selk, where in a freezing snowstorm the Danes were forced to give ground and fall back to Danevirke. Two days later, the Danish commander-in-chief, lieutenant general De Meza abandoned Danevirke to avoid being surrounded, withdrawing his army towards Als and Dybbol. The withdrawal was conducted on foot in a northern gale with driving snow, there were 600 casualties on the Danish side and their important heavy artillery was abandoned.\n\tWhen the hostilities began, the Danish army numbered some 38,000 men in four divisions, with 36,000 of them defending Danevirke, or "Danish Earthworks", the cornerstone of the Danish defence strategy in the area. The Prussian army numbered some 38,000 men and have been reinforced with 23,000 Austrian allies.\n\tThe Prussians having flanked the Danevirke defences advance to cut off the Danes as the Austrians pursue the withdrawing army. Latest reports coming in are from Sankelmark, where a Danish rear guard has held off an Austrian attack, allowing the main army to reach Dybbol.
Berlin, Prussia
