72
\tFollowing the retreat from Danevirke in the freezing cold in February, the Danish army took positions in the fortress of Dybbol, a previous site of fighting from the First Schleswig War. After two months of bombardment, this morning the Prussian guns stopped and the infantry charged. Despite artillery support from the Danish ironclad Rolf Krake, the Prussians soon seized control of the first line of defense and the redoubts. Only a brave stand made by the Danish 8th Brigade prevented a total massacre. During the counterattack, the Brigade lost half its men. In total, 3600 Danes and 1200 Prussians became casualties.\n\tTechnology played a major role in this battle. The modern rifled artillery fielded by the Prussians made the ill-prepared Dybbol position unsuitable for lengthy defense. The Dreyse needle-guns fielded by Prussian infantry allowed loading while lying down, while the Danish rifles required loading while standing, making the loading soldiers easy targets.
