\tOn May 9, the Battle of Heligoland was fought between the Danish and Austro-Prussian navies off the island of Heligoland, controlled by neutral Great Britain. Though Denmark claimed a tactical victory in the battle, the Danes were forced to end the blockade of the German coast. An armistice came into effect three days after the Battle of Heligoland.\n\tThe engagement was fought with wooden frigates. Edouard Suenson's Danish fleet was able to engage the Austrian screw frigates before the Prussians could join in, badly damaging Wilhelm von Tagetthoff's flagship Schwartzenberg. The Danes suffered some 70 casualties with one frigate damaged, while the Austro-Prussian force lost over 140 men with two frigates damaged.
