75
\tOn May 18, two newspapers published a story that President Abraham Lincoln had issued a proclamation for the conscription of 400,000 more men into the Union army. Share prices fell on the Stock Exchange when investors began to buy gold, and its value increased 10%.\n\tSuspicious that only two newspapers published such proclamation sparked investigation by a number of people, a former Union commanding general included. It was soon found, that the proclamation was fake and was delivered just as the night foreman had to make a decision whether to include it in the next day's paper.\n\tHearing of the case President Lincoln was enraged, and the two papers in question were closed and their offices seized by Union soldiers. Detectives tracked down the culprits. On May 21 they arrested Francis Mallison, a reporter who informed on his city editor Joseph Howard, Jr., who was also arrested. Howard had bought gold on margin during May 17, and profited immensely.

