\tThe Montana Territory was organized out of the existing Idaho Territory by Act of Congress and signed into law by President Abraham Lincoln on May 26. The areas east of the Continental Divide had been previously part of the Nebraska Territory and Dakota Territory and had been acquired by the United States in the Louisiana Purchase.\n\tThe Organic Act prescribes a somewhat standard organization for the territorial government of Montana. It establishes executive, judicial, and legislative branches of government, however the federal government holds a dominant role in administering the new territory. Particularly, Congress reserves the right to nullify any laws passed by the citizen-elected territorial legislature. The President of the United States appoints the most powerful positions in the territory, including the governor, secretary of the territory, and three members of the territorial supreme court, with the advice and consent of the U.S. Senate.

