\tThe Taiping Rebellion, or Civil War, has been waged in China since 1850 between the established Qing dynasty and the theocratic Taiping Heavenly Kingdom. The Third Battle of Nanking, fought between March 14 and July 19, was the effective end of the Taiping army and Nanking was the last major Taiping city to fall back under Imperial control. In the battle the Taiping losses amounted to a staggering 100,000 with a further 200,000 surrendering. In total more than a million troops were probably engaged in the battle.\n\tFor more than a decade, the Taiping occupied and fought across much of the mid and lower Yangtze valley, ultimately devolving into total civil war across the region. Estimates of the war dead range from 20 to 30 million, with another 30 million having fled from the conquered regions to foreign settlements or other parts of China.\n\tThe bloodletting is not over, as the victorious Qing forces launch waves of massacres.
