\tSince its independence, Uruguay has been ravaged by intermittent struggles between the Colorado and Blanco factions. The Colorado leader Venancio Flores launched the Liberating Crusade in 1863, an insurrection aimed at toppling Bernardo Berro, who presided over a Colorado–Blanco coalition government. The fusionism movement collapsed as the Colorados abandoned the coalition to join Flores' ranks. The Uruguayan Civil War quickly escalated.\n\tIn April, Brazil sent Jose Antonio Saraiva to negotiate with Atanasio Aguirre, who had succeeded Berro in Uruguay. Saraiva made an initial attempt to settle the dispute between the Blancos and Colorados. Faced with Aguirre's intransigence regarding Flores' demands, the Brazilian diplomat abandoned the effort and sided with the Colorados. On August 10, after a Brazilian ultimatum was refused, Saraiva declared that Brazil's military would begin exacting reprisals, declining to acknowledge a formal state of war.
