\tTo-day the first Geneva Convention was held. It defines the basis on which rest the rules of international law for the protection of the victims of armed conflicts.\n\tThe Swiss government invited the governments of all European countries, as well as the United States, Brazil, and Mexico, to attend an official diplomatic conference. Sixteen countries sent a total of twenty-six delegates to Geneva. The meeting was presided over by General Guillaume Henri Dufour. Signed at the Alhambra room in Geneva's Hotel de Ville on 22 August 1864, the conference adopted the first Geneva Convention "for the Amelioration of the Condition of the Wounded in Armies in the Field". The convention derives its obligatory force from the implied consent of the states which accept and plan to apply them in the conduct of their military operations.
