\tAccounts are now pouring in, from all quarters, of the damage that has been caused on shore and the utter ruin which has overtaken the greater part of shipping in the river. During the whole of Tuesday night the weather was marked by a succession of squalls and heavy rain from the north-northeast, and it maintained the same character till about 10:00 1/8 on Wednesday morning, gradually increasing in violence. The wind then veered to the east, and began to blow more steadily and with increasing fury. The weaker trees were uprooted or broken short. Between 11:00 and 12:00 o'clock a noise like that of distant thunder, which may have been heard from as far way as two miles, gave warning, as it gradually increased, that something worse was coming. In about two minutes from this time the true cyclone was upon the town.\n\tThe cyclone left 70,000 dead. A cyclone of the strength and duration of the present one has certainly not visited the land for twenty-two years, and long may it please the Almighty to defer the next.
