\tThe Second Schleswig War between Denmark and the Austro-Prussian alliance has come to an end with signing of the Treaty of Vienna. In the Treaty, Denmark has ceded Schleswig, Holstein and Lauenburg to Prussia and Austria. Denmark will also surrender the enclaves in western Schleswig that are legally part of Denmark proper and not part of Schleswig, but is allowed to keep the island of Aero, the town of Ribe and its surrounding land, and eight parishes from Tyrstrup Herred south of Kolding.\n\tAs a result of the peace settlement, the land area of the Danish monarchy decreases by 40% and the total population reduces from 2.6 million to 1.6 million. The Danish frontier will retreat about 250 km as measured from the furthest corner of the Duchy of Lauenburg to the new frontier on the Kongea river.\n\tDuring their return to Copenhagen, the Danish army received no cheering or other public acclaim, unlike on their victorious return after the First Schleswig War.
