\tEight days before the presidential election of 1864, Nevada, with a population of little more than 10,000, becomes the 36th state in the Union, despite lacking the minimum requisite 60,000 residents in order to become a state. Statehood was rushed to this date to help ensure Abraham Lincoln's reelection on November 8 and Republican dominance in Congress.\n\t Governor Nye was frustrated that previous attempts to send the constitution via overland mail and by sea had failed by October 24, so on October 26 the full text was sent by telegraph at a cost of more than 4000 dollars, making it the most costly telegraph on file. Finally, the response from Washington came to-day: "the pain is over, the child is born, Nevada this day was admitted into the Union".

