\tTerrible news from the Mississippi River, where the steamboat Sultana suddenly exploded while carrying some 2300 people, most of them paroled prisoners of war.\n\tThe enormous explosion of steam came from the rear top of the boilers, tearing through the crowded decks above, and completely demolishing the pilothouse. Without a pilot to steer the boat, the Sultana became a drifting, burning hulk. The terrific explosion flung some of the deck passengers into the water and destroyed a large section of the boat. Some seven hours after the expolsion, the Sultana sank.\n\tPassengers who survived the initial explosion had to risk their lives in the icy spring runoff of the Mississippi or burn with the boat. Many died by drowning or of hypothermia. Some survivors were plucked from the tops of semi-submerged trees along the Arkansas shore. A total of 760 survivors were hospitalized, and many a life could still be lost.

