\tThe Hickok–Tutt gunfight occurred on July 21 in the town square of Springfield, Missouri between Wild Bill Hickok and gambler Davis Tutt. Tutt and Hickok, both gamblers, had at one point been friends, despite the fact that Tutt was a Confederate Army veteran, and Hickok had been a scout for the Union Army.\n\tThe conflict came to a head during a game of poker at the Lyon House Hotel. Hickok was playing against several other local gamblers while Tutt stood nearby, loaning money as needed. Tutt humiliated Hickock, taking his watch. Days later the men entered into a duel, in which Tutt missed, but Hickock struck Tutt in the chest, killing him.\n\tThe next day, a warrant was issued for Hickok's arrest and to-day, two days later, he was arrested for murder.
