\tOn December 7, Confederate sympathizers from the Maritime Provinces, Canada, captured the American steamer Cheasapeake off the coast of Cape Cod. They entered the ship as normal passengers while in New York, and commandeered the vessel, during which action the ship's second engineer was killed.\n\tAs neutrality regulations forbade the bringing of prizes into British waters, Vernon Locke, the new commander of the vessel, sailed the ship to Canada to load coal. The ship was intercepted by American warships, which gave chase to Halifax. Three of the crew were captured, which violated British sovereignty and international laws. On this day, U.S. Secretary of State has told the British that he wants the ship returned and the captives put in jail and extradited to the states.\n\tWhile the Southern sympathisers believed they were engaging in an act of war because they had an official letter of marque from the Confederacy, it has been found their letter has no legal basis. Rather than being an official act of war, it is condemned as an act of piracy.
