\tThe state of Kentucky is becoming strategically important to both the North and the South. It has a large population and is a major producer of tobacco, corn and wheat. Looking from the South, the state offers a great defensive boundary along the Ohio River.\n\tKentucky Governor Beriah Magoffin is known to favor the right of secession, but is seeking all possible avenues to avoid it. Magoffin called a special session of the Kentucky General Assembly on December 27, 1860, and asked legislators for a convention of Kentuckians to decide the Commonwealth's course regarding secession. The majority of the General Assembly had Unionist sympathies, however, and declined the governor's request. But this does not mean the state will not secede in case of hostilities, especially if initiated by the U.S. Government. In case the state remains in the Union, it will most likely declare neutrality, but in this case it's unsure whether the North and the South would both resect it.\n\t
