26
\tNews from the slave states are coming in, and the story is the same: the public is outraged by Lincoln's decision to call the militia, to subdue the South, as it is commonly seen. The Northern agression, as Lincoln's recent action is called in the South, is said to be unjustifiable and uncalled for. Support for secession and the Confederacy increased considerably as a result, leading into furter states seceding. States, that probably would have remained in the Union without receiving the Government's order to form militia regiments in preparation for war.\n\tHow the militia call was received in the border states can be seen well in Kentucky Governor Magoffin's response to Lincoln: "President Lincoln, Washington, D.C. I will send not a man nor a dollar for the wicked purpose of subduing my sister Southern states. B. Magoffin."

