20-10-1864
A Raid in St.Albans, Vermont!
One Killed and Two Wounded!
Banks Robbed, Money Raised!
Raiders Arrested in Canada!
Money Recovered, Raiders Freed!
Bank Tellers Forced to Pledge Allegiance to the C.S.A.
95
\tTwenty-one Confederate soldiers have raided St.Albans, Vermont, on October 19, 1864. The raiders, led by Bennett H. Young, a previously captured but escaped Confederate soldier, moved in to Vermont from Province of Canada. They robbed three banks, capturing citizens and forcing them to pledge allegiance to the Confederacy. During the raid one U.S. citizen was killed.\n\tThe raiders met resistance, organized by Capt. George Conger of 1st Vermont Infantry Regiment, who was on leave. Conger's mob forced the raiders to retreat. The party reached Canada, where they were captured by the Canadian police.\n\tIn response to U.S. demands, the Canadian authorities returned the captured money, but will not extradite the raiders as they are considered soldiers under military orders. U.S. Secretary of State has expressed the angered Americans' opinion to his counterparts in London, stating "it is impossible to consider those proceedings as either legal, just or friendly towards the United States."
St.Albans, VT
-1
114
03-05-1861
U.S. Army Abandons Indian Territory!
Confederacy Captures Forts Intact!
Loyal Tribes on the Run!
Confederate Advance Guard Ambushed!
Bounty Placed on Black Beaver's Head!
Fort Arbuckle in Indian Territory.
96
\tThe U.S. army had five forts in the Indian Territory, safeguarding settlers and traders moving west, as well as local Indian tribes in need of protection. After the Battle of Fort Sumter, the situation in Indian Territory became untenable for the U.S. troops stationed there, as the Confederacy had been negotiating and securing alliances with the five civilized tribes, among them the Cherokee, Chickasaw and Creek. To escape capture, the Union commander in the area ordered the garrisons to abandon their posts.\n\tThe retreatign U.S. troops were helped by a Delaware trapper and scout called Black Beaver, who guided the soldiers to safety while observing pursuing Confederate militias. Black Beaver even helped ambushing the pursuing advance guard. In retaliation, his ranch was burned down and a bounty was placed on his head.\n\tThe Union garrisons were able to escape capture, reaching Fort Leavenworth in Kansas.

