116
01-01-1900
A Financial Crisis!
U.S. Credit Rating Deteriorated!
The Congress in an Emergency Meeting!
New Laws Being Drafted!
Free Fall of the Economy Feared!
Union Economy in Crisis.
51
\tThe Union is facing a financial crisis, as the nation's credit rating has deteriorated. To pay for the war effort, a constant stream of new debt has been issued, and the strain on the nation's economy has been such, that interest costs are now starting to getting out of hand.\n\tTo stabilize the spiralling economy, the Congress has forbidden any further recruitment and expansion of its military, until the required measures are taking effect, preventing a free fall of the Union's financial situation. The politicians are working day and night to pass new laws, allowing the economy to recover.\n\tAs military purchases and recruitment are put on hold, many suspect the nation will be vulnerable to attacks. Any further damage to the economy could be catastrophic, and it's feared the enemy may take advantage of this time of weakness and assume the aggressive.

